1464":"1440–1464","1465–1500":"1465–1500","1445–1494":"1445.–1494","1445":"1445.","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1464":"1464","1440":"1440","1494":"1494","about 1465":"oko 1465.","after 1464":"nakon 1464.","about 1494":"oko 1494.","England ":"Engleska, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Dymock, Gloucestershire, England":"Dymock, Gloucestershire, England"},"cs":{"1445–about 1494":"1445–okolo 1494","1440–1464":"1440–1464","1465–1500":"1465–1500","1445–1494":"1445–1494","1445":"1445","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1464":"1464","1440":"1440","1494":"1494","about 1465":"okolo 1465","after 1464":"po 1464","about 1494":"okolo 1494","England ":"Anglie, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, Anglie","Dymock, Gloucestershire, England":"Dymock, Gloucestershire, Anglie"},"da":{"1445–about 1494":"1445–omkring 1494","1440–1464":"1440–1464","1465–1500":"1465–1500","1445–1494":"1445–1494","1445":"1445","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1464":"1464","1440":"1440","1494":"1494","about 1465":"omkring 1465","after 1464":"efter 1464","about 1494":"omkring 1494","England ":"England, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Dymock, Gloucestershire, England":"Dymock, Gloucestershire, England"},"nl":{"1445–about 1494":"1445–circa 1494","1440–1464":"1440–1464","1465–1500":"1465–1500","1445–1494":"1445–1494","1445":"1445","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1464":"1464","1440":"1440","1494":"1494","about 1465":"circa 1465","after 1464":"na 1464","about 1494":"circa 1494","England ":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Dymock, Gloucestershire, England":"Dymock, Gloucestershire, England"},"en":{"1445–about 1494":"1445–about 1494","1440–1464":"1440–1464","1465–1500":"1465–1500","1445–1494":"1445–1494","1445":"1445","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1464":"1464","1440":"1440","1494":"1494","about 1465":"about 1465","after 1464":"after 1464","about 1494":"about 1494","England ":"England, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Dymock, Gloucestershire, England":"Dymock, Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Smith","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name denoting a worker in metal, especially iron, such as a blacksmith or farrier, from Middle English <i>smith</i> ‘smith’ (Old English <i>smith</i>, probably a derivative of <i>smītan</i> ‘to strike, hammer’). Early examples are also found in the Latin form   Faber  . Metal-working was one of the earliest occupations for which specialist skills were required, and its importance ensured that this term and its equivalents in other languages were the most widespread of all occupational surnames in Europe. Medieval smiths were important not only in making horseshoes, plowshares, and other domestic articles, but above all for their skill in forging swords, other weapons, and armor. This is also the most frequent of all surnames in the US. It is very common among African Americans and Native Americans (see also 5 below). This surname (in any of the two possible English senses; see also below) is also found in Haiti. See also   Smither  .","English: from Middle English <i>smithe</i> ‘smithy, forge’ (Old English <i>smiththe</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in or by a blacksmith's shop, occupational, for someone who worked in one, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Smitha in King's Nympton (Devon). Compare   Smithey  .","Irish and Scottish: sometimes adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Gobhann</b>, Irish <b>Mac Gabhann</b> ‘son of the smith’. See   McGowan  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Smithe","meanings":["(1997: 115;2007: 306; 2010: NA)","English: variant of   Smith  ."]},{"name":"Smither","meanings":["English (Surrey): occupational name from Middle English <i>smith(i)ere</i>, <i>smeth(i)ere</i> ‘blacksmith’, a derivative of Middle English <i>smithen</i>, <i>smethen</i>, ‘to make (something) in metal, to forge’. Compare   Smith  ."]},{"name":"Smithey","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): from Middle English <i>smithi</i> ‘smithy, forge’ (Old Norse <i>smithja</i>), used either as a topographic name for someone who lived in or by a blacksmith's shop, or an occupational name for someone who worked in one. Compare   Smith   and   Smead  ."]},{"name":"Smyth","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Ronan, Aidan, Brigid, Conor, Eoin, Malachy, Paddy.","English: variant of   Smith  . This form of the surname is particularly common Ireland."]},{"name":"Smythe","meanings":["English (London): variant of   Smith  ."]},{"name":"McGowan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Siobhan, Cormac, Seamus, Aileen, Colm, Eithne, Kieran, Niall, Paddy.","Scottish and Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac (a') Ghobhainn</b> or <b>Mac Gobhann</b> (Scottish) or <b>Mac (an) Ghabhann</b> (Irish), ‘son of (the) smith’. This name has also been Anglicized as   Smith   and   Smithson  ."]},{"name":"Smead","meanings":["English:","occupational name from Middle English <i>smeth(e)</i> ‘smith’, a phonetic variant of   Smith   1 that was widespread in medieval England, especially in south-eastern and south-western counties.","topographic, occupational, and habitational name from Middle English <i>smethe</i> ‘smithy, forge’ (Old English <i>smethe</i>), a side form of   Smith   2, for someone who lived and worked at a blacksmith's, or who lived in or came from a place so named, such as Smeeth (Kent) or Smeed Farm in Hastingleigh (Kent). Compare the synonymous   Smithey  ."]},{"name":"Faber","meanings":["German, Dutch, French (Alsace and Lorraine), and Danish; Slovak and Czech (mainly <b>Fáber</b>): occupational name from Latin <i>faber</i> ‘blacksmith’. At the time of the Reformation, it was much used as a humanistic name, a translation into Latin of vernacular surnames such as German   Schmidt   and Dutch   Smit  . Compare   Fabri   and   Fauber  .","History: In North America, this surname was originally also part of a title. It was François Lefebvre, <i>sieur</i> Duplessis Faber from Paris, France, whose title <i>sieur Duplessis Faber</i> was shortened into the surname <i>Faber</i>. He married Marie-Madeleine Chorel in Champlain, QC, in 1689."]}]},{"name":"Ann","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Anne .  In the U.S. <i>Ann</i> is the more frequent spelling."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":10,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Ann Smith was born in 1445, in Essex, England. She had at least 1 daughter with John Lettice. She died about 1494, in her hometown, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1445–about 1494":"1445–umbes 1494","1440–1464":"1440–1464","1465–1500":"1465–1500","1445–1494":"1445–1494","1445":"1445","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1464":"1464","1440":"1440","1494":"1494","about 1465":"umbes 1465","after 1464":"pärast 1464","about 1494":"umbes 1494","England ":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Dymock, Gloucestershire, England":"Dymock, Gloucestershire, England"},"fi":{"1445–about 1494":"1445–noin 1494","1440–1464":"1440–1464","1465–1500":"1465–1500","1445–1494":"1445–1494","1445":"1445","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1464":"1464","1440":"1440","1494":"1494","about 1465":"noin 1465","after 1464":"1464 jälkeen","about 1494":"n